ckinghamshire, England":"Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mauduit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Mawditt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mawditt","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>mal-duit</i> ‘badly brought up, ill educated’ (Latin  <i>male doctus</i>)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Mauduit Baron of Hanslope was born in 1144, in Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Mauduit II, was 53 and his mother, Maude Hanslape, was 66. He married Isabel Hedwig St Liz in 1160, in Hanslope, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 2 October 1194, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1144–2 October 1194":"1144–2. oktoober 1194","1098–Female":"1098–Surnud","1123–1184":"1123–1184","1128–1187":"1128–1187","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1134–1210":"1134–1210","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1144–1194":"1144–1194","1158–1191":"1158–1191","1135–1171":"1135–1171","1171–1221":"1171–1221","1092–1158":"1092–1158","1079–1171":"1079–11